name: Lovely Garden Studio in Santa Cruz
summary: Adorable, eco-friendly studio apartment, tucked in a lovely and peaceful garden setting in the Live Oak neighborhood. Close to Capitola, Santa Cruz, and the ocean. The studio has a full kitchen, cozy sleeping loft, outdoor hot tub, & more!
space: This adorable studio is perfect for one or two people. It has a cozy sleeping loft with a comfy queen bed, a full kitchen, a bathroom with a lovely tiled shower, walk-in closet space, and a sweet living room area with a vaulted ceiling.  Constructed using passive solar design, it stays just the right temperature all through the year and the south-facing windows and French doors allow light to stream in all day long.  On colder days, a radiant-heated floor system provides warmth by pumping water through tubing embedded in a beautifully-stained concrete floor, radiating heat through the rest of the house.  Finally, a photovoltaic solar system produces electricity from the sun!  The studio is nestled in a garden of winding flagstone paths, fruit trees, herbs, edible leafy greens, ferns, and low water-use flowering ornamental plants that attracts birds, squirrels, butterflies, and more.

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood has a mix of commercial and residential properties. It is diverse in income levels and is at the edge of a riparian corridor, so it has a tiny bit of a wilderness feel even though it's in the middle of town and really close to Highway 1. On my street are two nurseries, an auto mechanic, and a trailer park. The house/lot right next to mine is currently vacant and boarded up.  I am about 1.5 miles from the ocean and am close to hiking trails in the hills with redwoods and streams. Within one mile are popular restaurants such as The Shadowbrook, Cafe Cruz, Chaminade, Gayle's Bakery, and a new brew pub, (website hidden)'s Alley is a popular bar with live music several nights of the week. You can drive to 41st Ave. in less than 5 minutes where there are coffee shops, a mall, and restaurants. In less than 2 miles is the Santa Cruz yacht harbor where you can rent kayaks, surfboards or stand up paddleboards- or board a sailing vessel for a sunset cruise on the Monterey Bay. Ca
notes: The freezer is tiny; not much more than a pint of ice cream can easily fit inside of it.
transit: Parking is easy as I provide a place to park right in the driveway. A major bus line (Santa Cruz Metro) is located about 5 blocks from the studio.  It is easy to bike around Santa Cruz and Capitola as there are many designated bike lanes. There are places to rent bikes if you want.  The best way to get here from the airport is to rent a car or take the bus (easier from San Jose, more challenging from SFO).
host_about:
Hi!

I am so happy you are looking at my adorable studio as a possible place to stay. I think you will love it! I've been living in Santa Cruz for 17 years and in this studio in the Live Oak neighborhood for 18 months. I feel grateful everyday to live in such a wonderful little place. When I first moved in I thought "this place would be an amazing Airbnb spot", but couldn't bring myself to share it at that time. I wanted it all to myself! :) Now that I'm settled in and have everything arranged just so, I feel excited to share the bounty with others such as yourself. 

As I described, the studio is eco-friendly, beautiful, and is tucked in a magical wonderland of a garden with a hot tub and an adjacent open lot that makes it feel a bit on the wild side. My landlords are some of the sweetest and most generous people I know and share the backyard with me. 

One of my favorite things about this place is how the moonlight streams in through the loft windows when it is out at night and how I can sometimes hear a great-horned owl hooting in the distance. I also love walking the short flagstone path to get into the hot tub almost every night before I go to bed. The hot tub is shared by my landlords and is located on their back porch, but I pretty much have it all to myself whenever I go. 

My favorite places in Santa Cruz to explore are the ones I can easily bike to from my home. Now that I am living here, that includes the hiking trails on the Chaminade land, Schwan Lake State Park, and the many beaches in our area (especially Black's Beach and Seabright Beach). I also love exploring Wilder Ranch and Natural Bridges State Parks on the westside. I would be happy to point you to some of the many local sweet spots. 

I've practiced yoga for more than 20 years and have been meditating daily for almost 9 years. Because of this (I think), my home has a really peaceful vibe to it that I hope you will be able to feel. 

Please be in touch if you have any questions. I look forward to hearing from you!

I am a professional person, and I love to garden, travel and enjoy good food. I love music ( our local Jazz club, the Kuumbwa is amazing!)  I am also a dancer, and love to move in many ways. Paris, Prague, London, Florence and Sienna are favorite places abroad, NYC , Portland, Nashville are good in the States.

As a hostess, I am pretty hands off... will love to show you on a map, our local farmer's markets, where the good local restaurants are and how to walk to the harbor ( four blocks from the house) and beach. I like things clean and simple; prefer the outdoors or a big city. There is no TV in the house, but a great sound system...I speak French fluently, can get by, barely, in German, Italian and Spanish.

neighborhood_overview: A short walk up the road will bring you to the entrance of the Pogonip, a natural preserve, with endless trails and beautiful views. We are less than ten minutes from all of the excitement at the Boardwalk (we like to ride our bikes, just coming back up the hill is a work out — takes about 15 minutes- this way we don’t have to pay for parking!). Downtown is brisk walk or a short 5 min. drive.
notes: We do not allow pets.  Three night min. stay.  At times we might have a large camper parked in the drive way. The camper is not occupied.
transit: The public bus system is at the end of the street. It will take you across town. There is a ZipCar location nearby, if you are carless. Otherwise, Santa Cruz is a very bike friendly city and you can nearly bike anywhere (just bring a lock).
host_about:
I moved with my family from Palo Alto to Santa Cruz about two years ago and we absolutely love it here.  Santa Cruz is full of excitement and beauty, I feel I am on a vacation, every morning when I wake up. 
I am originally from Germany. I love traveling, meeting people and exploring new locations and cultures.  Every year, my brother and I will pick a place to visit, that neither of us have been to. However, my favorite city is still my home base, Hamburg in Germany.

host_about:
I was lucky enough to have lived in France for a few years and traveled extensively throughout Europe. Many of my adventures were with three small children in tow so I'm fairly well versed in all things children and how to vacation with kids successfully. I still have two boys underfoot(13&15) so while we were putting our beach home together I was trying to make it comfortable and functional. I spent many summers in a lakeside cabin in Michigan and never once worried about whether I had sand on my feet as I traipsed through the house.   My idea of a perfect vacation is to be able to walk everywhere, life as a mom requires far too much driving! Our girl in Santa Cruz allows me to stroll to Pacific Avenue(groceries, restaurants and movies) as well as a one block mosey to the sand. In my opinion if I can avoid getting in my car, it's a WIN!

 I'm outnumbered and live with all guys so my movie habits seem to involve a lot of exploding robots or superheroes. I'm also more apt to be found at the pizza place with the Samurai wielding pizza thrower than I am at the "new place." My youngest is an avid hamburger fan so currently we are eating our way through the Burger Joints.  Betty's Burgers is the top ranked  in Santa Cruz to date. (one location up the hill and one on Pacific Avenue) Their happy hour pitcher of mojitos is not bad either. Keep in mind the food critic is a 12yo boy-he will agree that the Buttery on Soquel Ave. (with their outside picnic tables) is still our top ranked destination to eat breakfast or lunch in the Cruz.

name: Guest bedroom in Victorian home
space: A redwood-floored sun-filled, shuttered bedroom with arched windows and gabled ceiling in a unique 1860s home in Santa Cruz.  My unique 'Carpenter Gothic' is one of the earliest houses built by settlers in the mid 19th. century. Both room and  adjacent bathroom (shower, toilet, washbasin) are fully remodelled and immaculately clean on the second floor of my home. The guest room is private, quiet, and  has its own entrance staircase. It also offers panoramic views of the Monterey Bay in one of Santa Cruz's oldest, safest, quietest neighborhoods. Walking distance to downtown through other historic areas.  1/2 acre of mature gardens and an 'orchidarium' surround this unique house on the hill. The main bus line to UCSC has a stop 3 minutes' walk away; the main terminus is  a 15" walk - all downhill! name: Charming Forest Cabin in Santa Cruz
summary: This quiet, one room, hexagonal gazebo-type cabin is located down the hill from the main housing unit it is a part of. The large windows give panoramic views of the forest all around, and you can also enjoy the fresh air from the attached deck.
space: The cabin is nestled in the woods, with plenty of incredible natural views, which paired with the quiet atmosphere, make for the perfect getaway spot, whether you're alone or traveling with someone.  There are two large windows, a sliding glass door, and a smaller window that afford plenty of views of the greenery all around. All the windows have good blinds so you don't have to worry about too much sun getting in. There is also a skylight which lets in natural light that makes the daytime in the cabin almost as cool as the night.  The cabin's night lighting includes two large spherical paper lanterns one yellow, one blue, as well as solid orange holiday type lights. There's a fiberoptic light in the skylight, as well as a smattering of other multicolored lights around the room which definitely give it a uniquely cool atmosphere.  One thing to NOTE is that there is no bathroom in the cabin, you'll have to walk up stairs to the main house to use the bathrooms there.

neighborhood_overview: The neighborhood is quiet, family friendly, and very very very safe. There are many interesting houses on the block, along with some hiking trails and beautiful meadows within a 10 minute walk. The beach is about a 10 minute drive, as well as downtown Santa Cruz. Capitola and Soquel are near too. This location is very central to everything.
notes: My name is Nicholas/Nikki/Nick, I'm a pilot and musician, and am often not home. I thought this beautiful cabin was going to waste during my time not here (very often), so I arranged with my landlord and housemates to have guests over to add some new energy to our unique house.  Everyone that lives in our house dabbles in the arts, appreciates good food, music, and company. They are all just as capable of talking for hours as they are minding their own matters, it's up to you to engage them however you please.  You will always have fresh towels and sheets upon checkin, and if you need anything Paul the main cool cat/landlord/house owner will be able to help. In rare instances where he isn't answering your calls I'll be available as well. Another thing to NOTE: getting from the street to the cabin and cabin to main house requires a fair bit of climbing/descending of stairs, it isn't very conducive to those who may have injuries  or handicapped air bnbers that may have issues with stairs
transit: The house is located 1 mile up the hill from the nearest bus stop, we are currently working on having bikes available for our guests. Car parking is ample on our street. Info on public transit from SJC airport: (website hidden) SFO is similar plus a BART ride from the airport to Millbrae, then a CalTrain ride to San Jose Diridon Station, then the Hwy 17 Express to Downtown Santa Cruz. Public transit from the Bay Area airports is doable, but often difficult and requires planning and substantial time.
host_about:
I'm Nicholas/Nikki/Nick (whatever suits you). I'm a 23 year old multilingual pilot and musician that loves to travel and enjoy the destinations life takes me to. I like to cook, hang with friends, go on hikes, swim at the beach, among many other things. I love being in nature whenever I can, and try to enjoy all the journeys life throws at me. I play a few instruments but tend to play mostly sax and piano in my spare time, whenever I'm home I have a few bands I play with to keep the creative side of me alive. As fun as it is flying all around the world, I think it's just as important to cultivate creativity whenever you can. 

Paul, who you'll be interacting with during your stay, is a true audiophile, and loves his music. He's an artist in his free time, but works as an air conditioning engineer. His art is all around the house and makes it one of the coolest places to live ever. Paul loves to talk about anything, listen to music, go kayaking, and loves all things organic.

Sit on the front patio, enjoy the sun, read, co
neighborhood_overview: A quintessential beach town neighborhood and tiny piece of paradise.  Walk the nearby path along cliff and watch surfers, and sea otters and maybe spot Dolphins or whales. Many guests never leave the neighborhood or use their cars.
notes: World  class surf from 1 to 6 blocks away - Pleasure Point, the Hook, Sewer Peak, 26th Ave.   Beautiful beaches and classic Boardwalk.   World class MTB. Rent top of the line bikes from Santa Cruz Bikes.  There are miles of beautiful single track mountain biking and hiking through the Redwoods.  Santa Cruz county has more open space as a percentage than any other county in Californai.  There are also quite winding  backroads to roadbike or motorcycle on, in addition to award winning local breweries and wineries. Monterey and Carmel are less than 1 hour away, and San Francisco is 1.5 hours.
transit: If relaxation is your goal, you can easily walk or ride bikes everywhere you would need to go -restaurants, grocery stores, coffee shops, beach within 1 block  or 2 miles.  Downtown Santa Cruz and the Boardwalk (both 5 miles away) are accessible by car, bus or bike.
host_about: Casual, outdoor-loving active person.  When I am not surfing, biking, or trail running ,I am likely reading.  I love to travel and learn new things, and I love to spend time with my girlfriend and Jack Russell.

Surfing at Cowell's Beach, riding the roller coaster, splashing in the surf, bowling, laser tag, skateboard park, walk ten minutes in the other direction and there is downtown and Pacific avenue, full of places to eat, shop or catch a movie!
transit: The bus to UC is across the street. It is a ten minute walk to the main bus termil in Santa Cruz that runs buses from all over the Bay Area and to SJ Intl. Airport.
host_about:
I was lucky enough to have lived in France for a few years and traveled extensively throughout Europe. Many of my adventures were with three small children in tow so I'm fairly well versed in all things children and how to vacation with kids successfully. I still have two boys underfoot(13&15) so while we were putting our beach home together I was trying to make it comfortable and functional. I spent many summers in a lakeside cabin in Michigan and never once worried about whether I had sand on my feet as I traipsed through the house.   My idea of a perfect vacation is to be able to walk everywhere, life as a mom requires far too much driving! Our girl in Santa Cruz allows me to stroll to Pacific Avenue(groceries, restaurants and movies) as well as a one block mosey to the sand. In my opinion if I can avoid getting in my car, it's a WIN!

 I'm outnumbered and live with all guys so my movie habits seem to involve a lot of exploding robots or superheroes. I'm also more apt to be found at the pizza place with the Samurai wielding pizza thrower than I am at the "new place." My youngest is an avid hamburger fan so currently we are eating our way through the Burger Joints.  Betty's Burgers is the top ranked  in Santa Cruz to date. (one location up the hill and one on Pacific Avenue) Their happy hour pitcher of mojitos is not bad either. Keep in mind the food critic is a 12yo boy-he will agree that the Buttery on Soquel Ave. (with their outside picnic tables) is still our top ranked destination to eat breakfast or lunch in the Cruz.

Just footsteps down the street is a gorgeous beach with views of two lighthouses and the gateway to the harbor.  This beach has fine dining, a coffee house, a taco bar, and kayak rentals. name: Garden Cottage in the Heart of SC!
summary: Come stay in this modern and cozy cottage in the heart of Santa Cruz!  During the day, enjoy a short walk to surfing, beach, boardwalk, wharf, and downtown.  Then come relax on your deck amongst the fruit trees!
space: ***Please note we collect the 11% Transient Occupancy Tax.  This tax is included in the price Come relax in this open floor plan (there is no door between the bedroom and living room), one bedroom, one bath cottage.   In the morning, grab a cup of complementary coffee or tea and enjoy it on the sunny deck.  Make yourself at home with a fridge, microwave, and coffee machine (no sink or stove). The large and sunny bedroom has all new furniture, queen bed, large walk-in closet, and looks out onto the deck. Hang out in the living room on the comfy futon (which folds out into a bed) and watch free Netflix, Amazon Prime, and HBO GO on the LCD TV with Roku player (no cable tv or satellite). Free wi-fi access :)  Or, grab a book from the bookcase or a board game. Towels, sheets, pillows, and comforters for the bed and the futon provided.  Travel crib available upon request. One parking pass provided for on-street parking.

neighborhood_overview: Our cottage is in (we think!) the perfect location to enjoy all that Santa Cruz has to offer - we're only blocks from downtown, the boardwalk, the wharf, and Cowell's beach.  You can walk to the beach for coffee and breakfast at the Picnic Basket in the morning, bask in the sun on the deck in the cottage in the afternoon, and then walk downtown for dinner at night. Also, the walking path and pontoon path in Neary Lagoon is a hidden treasure, with all sorts of beautiful wildlife.
notes: Like many other popular rentals, we have been contacted by the city to collect a transient occupancy tax of 11% of the total cost (before AirBNB fees). I'm sure all rentals will be collecting this very soon (all hotels currently collect it) - help us in being compliant with the law :).  The tax is included in the price and breaks down as follows: Summer weekday price: (phone number hidden) Summer weekend price: (phone number hidden) Winter weekday price:(phone number hidden) Winter weekend price: (phone number hidden) Cleaning fee: 30 + 11% = 33 Each additional person per night over 2 people: 10 + 11% = 11 We are very pleased to share our living space with you.  Occasionally, our very friendly medium-sized dog, Kona, pays a visit and roams the yard.  Please be sure you are comfortable with this! Two night minimum if staying Saturday night (i.e. Friday and Saturday or Saturday and Sunday).
host_about:
Hi!  My husband and I are very excited to be sharing our living space with you!  We love living in Santa Cruz - there is so much to do and it is such a beautiful place to live.  

We love hiking, rock climbing, skiing, surfing (my husband), and spending time with friends and family.  We are looking forward to meeting new and interesting people and showing you the best of Santa Cruz!

neighborhood_overview: Seabright/midtown Santa Cruz is a unique treasure-filled neighborhood. You might find tiny poetry stations & lending libraries tucked in along the sidewalk. Close to the Seabright Brewery, the railroad trestle (see the movie Lost Boys) is the secret shortcut to the Main Beach & Boardwalk.  Walking distance: + Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk + San Lorenzo River + Seabright Beach + Santa Cruz Harbor + Climbing gym & yoga + Coffee shops, bakeries & restaurants + Organic & specialty markets
notes: I'm happy to share restaurant recommendations or advise you on getting around :)

Hello, my name is Pat and the handsome fellow in the pictures with me is my husband, Richard. We are very relaxed, go with the flow kind of people.  Richard is a retired, former printing company owner, the inventor of a successful golf product. I quit my law librarian day job some years ago to have a more flexible lifestyle. We are outdoors enthusiasts, we enjoy interesting people and diverse cultures.  We believe if everyone had the opportunity to travel it would be a much better world.

Five things we can't live w/o : good friends, good coffee, good wine, good food and good health, and not necessarily in that order.

We decided to join AirBnB based on the enthusiastic reviews our friends give the program (they are guests, not hosts). We enjoy meeting people and sharing the incredible area we are so fortunate to live in... so we decided to give 'hosting' a try. You are cordially invited to visit us in beautiful Bonny Doon!

summary: We are honored to treat you to Jasmine Garden Oasis—3 blocks from beaches. Jasmine Studio upstairs, Ginger & Peach Rooms downstairs. Set back from the street, our space is bright and clean surrounded by gardens--renewing for your heart, body & soul.
space: We are Marie & Peter, a married couple hosting you in our home located three blocks from the beach. Our three rooms offer either a queen bed (Jasmine Studio and Peach Room) or double futon bed (Ginger Room), with optional optional single temporary bed in each room, and 10% discount with each additional room you book. neighborhood_overview: Our neighborhood is a relatively quiet neighborhood with an assortment of people who enjoy living near the beach--including long-time residents, families, retired people, UCSC students, and surfers interspersed to keep it characteristic of Santa Cruz.  Two blocks away is a modest shopping center which hosts the local farmer's market on Sunday mornings. A handful of eateries and a coffee shop, from fast food to upscale dining, line the two blocks toward the beaches. A back way to the beach (our special secret) is three lovely blocks, two of which are walking/biking trails, one lined with Cypress trees, and the next along a lagoon lined with Eucalyptus trees. The Harbor and Crows Nest restaurant and nightclub are a several blocks to the west along the shore. Downtown Santa Cruz is 3 miles west and Capitola, a quaint seaside town, is 2 miles east. Both are easily accessible by bike lanes, public transportation and car.
notes: The required Transient Occupancy tax for AirB&B rooms in Santa Cruz county is 11%. See below for more details. We ask that you pay us in the blue envelope you will see on the desk when you arrive, either with a personal check or cash.  Our house has three AirBnB rooms, and sound travels in our home, so please be considerate of others during our quiet hours (9:00pm to 7:30am). Because we are a shoes-free home, slip-on slippers and slip-on garden shoes are handy to leave inside and outside the door. Check-in time is 3:00pm and check-out time is 11:00am. Feel free to leave luggage on the porch and make yourselves at home if you wish to arrive early or stay late. Santa Cruz area has been suffering a severe water shortage, and water is rationed. We have installed low flush toilets, we re-use grey water when possible, and we ask our guests to minimize their water usage.  NOTE: If you are interested in receiving massage, acupuncture, cranio-sacral therapy or Rolfing here, then message me and
transit: Our location is very convenient for public transportation. The bus stop is around the corner that takes you directly to downtown Santa Cruz. The local bus service hooks up with service to San Jose, Caltrain, and all the Bay Area Transit systems including both San Jose and San Francisco Airports. From the airport, use Bay Area Transit system to Diridon Station in San Jose. From there you can catch the Hwy 17 Express to Santa Cruz. From the Santa Cruz downtown station take Santa Cruz Metro Bus 66 or 68 (Live Oak) to the bus stop nearest the intersection of 17th and Portola. The intersection is 2 blocks from our house. Car travel is convenient . . . street parking with no meters along our street. We use our carport as an unloading/loading zone for our guests' convenience. Bike travel is a dream with rentals accessible, bike lanes all through town, and longer bike trails in the area.
host_about: We, Peter & Marie, are a married couple who relish offering our sweet space & location to guests. We enjoy living in a tranquil atmosphere and want to share this with others of like mind at our home, Jasmine Garden Oasis near the Sea. It is a modest home tucked away in a modest neighborhood three blocks from the beach in east Santa Cruz with three B&B rooms--2 rooms downstairs with a shared bath and a private separate studio upstairs. We keep gentle gardens and cosy comfortable atmosphere for people who want a time of  renewal for body and soul. Mornings we visit the quiet beach to listen to the surf and watch the dawn, and evenings the dusk. We invite guests to join us for early morning yoga and/or meditation in our common room or on the lawn by the pond and waterfall. We have a list of massage therapists and acupuncturists who have offered to deliver their services to our guests in their private rooms. A lovely couple, Melissa and Rodney, are caretaking for us through Sept. 30 while we travel. We know you will enjoy their hosting in our home!

neighborhood_overview: We are next door to the tasting room for a good local winery, and there are many more wineries in the area.  1 mile up the road is an ecological preserve with great hiking.  It is 3 miles down the mountain to a nice beach.  The roads around us don't have a lot of cars so the area is great for bicycling.  Go north on Highway One and you are at Davenport, an old whaling town with a nice restaurant and another nice beach.  Just further north on the coast is Ano Nuevo State Park, where the giant elephant seals raise their babies on the beach each spring.  Also close by are Big Basin State Park (with old growth redwoods), Henry Cowell State Park and many other great parks.   And of course, we are only 13 miles north of the wonderful town of Santa Cruz.
notes: The closest grocery stores are in Felton (New Leaf) and Santa Cruz (Safeway, New Leaf and Costco). If you plan to go by the pond in the evening, bring mosquito repellent.
transit: We are in a rural area so guests will need to have a car.
host_about:
I'm an electrician, been in this area for 30 years.  Moved here from the Bay Area. Somewhat of a mountain man. Love outdoor activities -- hiking, nature walks, beaches, dogs, riding Harley's, etc. 

I like people, and want to provide a quiet place so people guests can relax.  I am a part-time caretaker for this property.

host_about: I graduated from University of California at Santa Cruz (UCSC) back in the days when the students adopted the banana slug as the school mascot, there were no grades and Natural Bridges State Beach Park had two natural bridges over the ocean. After four years, I was ready to leave Santa Cruz for life in the big city- San Francisco! I re-discovered Santa Cruz after being gone for almost two decades and planning my 20th college reunion. The timing coincided with the birth of our child. I experienced what the area had to offer and was impressed by the changes and reassured by the familiarity. Santa Cruz is an easy getaway from our San Francisco family home. We find the drive very therapeutic with the transition from our fast paced lives to our Santa Cruz sanctuary. The 75 minute drive to Santa Cruz from San Francisco is beautiful through the evergreens on Highway 17 or by the ocean on Highway 1.

description: This newly renovated 1918 carriage house in a quiet family neighborhood is a short walk to the beach and restaurants. The small home is a sunny and peaceful retreat from all the fun you will find stepping outside its door. This cottage is just four blocks from Seabright Beach, two blocks from Seabright Brewery. The entire carriage house consists of a 535 sq ft apartment that sits on top of two carriage bays. If you were coming down from San Francisco in 1920, you would keep the horse and carriage in the bays, then go out to hear music, sit by the roaring beach bonfires, then return to your cottage to rest.  Today, the carriage bays have a couple of bikes you can use to explore the beach and music scene. It has  beach cha
neighborhood_overview: The Seabright neighborhood is perfectly located between the boardwalk and the marina. Both are just under a mile from the cottage. It is warmer and sunnier than the rest of town and therefore called the "banana-belt" of Santa Cruz. Seabright beach is your "classic beach". The wide sands stretch beneath the bluffs. The facilities are decent with flush toilets and an outdoor shower. Lifeguards keep you safe during the summer season. There are fire rings for evening bonfires. There are a handful of restaurants in the heart of Seabright, and you are only 1.5 miles from all the shops and eateries on Pacific Street, downtown. You are in the middle of everything, yet living on a quiet neighborhood street, perfect for peaceful evenings at home.
notes: ABOUT THE HOUSE My husband Albert and I live at the cottage part time. We also live with my daughter when work requires us to be in the valley, which at the moment is too often. Thus, the house is not a pure vacation rental; we have personal belongings there. Half the dresser is empty for guests' clothes, more than half the closet is empty. You will see our toothbrushes in the medicine cabinet, etc. We live minimally so there is no clutter, but we do not move out between guests. There is a security camera watching for uninvited intruders.  There is a second house on the property with long term renters. They have a small dog and two cats. The yard is divided in two so you each have your own space.  There is no dishwasher and no microwave. ABOUT SANTA CRUZ Watch sailboat races at the Santa Cruz Small Craft Harbor on Wednesday nights 6:30 to 8:30 PM April through October. Capitola Art & Wine Festival September 12 & 13 from 10 AM to 6 PM. FREE Movies on the Beach: Wednesday nights at 9:00p

transit: Walking and biking is how we think it is best, but you can easily take a 10 minute walk to the bus station downtown or bus stops mere blocks away. If you are driving, there is first come, first serve parking in the driveway (room for 3 cars) and street parking.
host_about:
Hello, my name is Charlotte and I am excited to be a host for Airbnb. I love meeting new people and look forward to hosting folks coming through town. I live right next door to this rental with my adorable Jack Russell, Jerry Lee, so I will be available and nearby if you have any questions. 

I am a textile artist and own my own small business called Stand West, where I design and hand make a range of luxury, eco conscious accessories using custom dyed fabrics and mostly repurposed materials. If you are extra curious check out @standwestcreations on Instagram. 

In addition to Stand West I am a Hip Hop Dance Teacher and work with Crush Sunglasses (a company based in the LA area) as their Northern California lifestyle rep. 

Despite growing up in beautiful Colorado and having the opportunity to explore every state in the USA, Santa Cruz has a strong hold on my heart. Here I spend the majority of my free time at the skate park located just a few blocks from Riverside Ranch, running on West Cliff, visiting the farmers markets that are held every day of the week throughout town, taking my dog to the beach, hiking in the redwoods with friends, and working with the community to make this city even better then it already is. 

I have been blessed beyond my own imagination to travel many places across the globe through the benefits of having  a mother as a Airline Stewardess. Because of all of my experiences being away from home I have a huge heart for making sure that your stay is the best it can be. Staying somewhere that feels like home, rather then in a hotel, makes all of the difference for me when I am exploring new places. Thank God for Airbnb. ; ) 

I hope to have the chance to get to know you and whether or not you decide to stay at Riverside Ranch I'll be wishing for you the best experiences while you are here in Santa Cruz. 

Light and Love!

Charlie

neighborhood_overview: We love being so close to downtown and being able to ride bikes and walk everywhere! There will be some suggested activities including where to rent bikes and get surfing lessons when you arrive. The neighborhood is a very eclectic mix. Many single, 30 something professionals, young Latino families, college kids, hipsters, travelers, and artists. We love the hip, young, colorful vibe.
notes: Santa Cruz is known for petty theft... no matter where you stay... lock up the cars and gates to keep bikes safe.
transit: With so much to do within walking distance including grocery shopping and the beach... you really don't need a car.  However there's plenty of street parking and most of downtown is metered parking. Our neighborhood is perfect for biking, bring your own or rent one from one of the bike shops nearby.  The bus system around Santa Cruz is relatively good. There's a bus stop on our street.  (website hidden) Taxi's are readily available and Uber is here too! We recommend the Santa Cruz Flyer if you need an airport ride. (website hidden) The closest airport to Santa Cruz is San Jose (35 minutes) - airport code: SJC. Other airports would be Oakland (OAK), San Francisco (SFO), Monterey (MRY)

space: The beauty of the Santa Cruz mountains awaits you! Our home is situated exceptionally well, balancing accessibility with seclusion. Ten minutes to Felton's quaint main street,  fifteen minutes to the beach, twenty minutes to downtown Santa Cruz, ninety minutes to San Francisco up scenic Highway 1. But when you are sipping tea or a beer on the porch, you'll hear nothing but the hummingbirds and the wind in the trees.  We have two bedrooms for rent in our home. neighborhood_overview: Bonny Doon is a charming community in the mountains, blending serious old-timers with vacation-home implants, and intentionally keeping itself "rural and natural." The people here consciously cultivate a sense of community and are genuinely friendly.  The beauty of the Santa Cruz mountains is phenomenal. Our home is centrally located between several state parks: Big Basin, Henry Cowell (to which we are adjacent), Wilder Ranch and Waddell Beach.  The beach town of Davenport is fifteen minutes away, and boasts a good restaurant (the Roadhouse), a locally-famous cafe/bakery, frequent live music, and a sprinkling of shops, all with Pacific views. The mountain towns of Felton, Ben Lomond, and Boulder Creek area also nearby and quaint.  Nearby Santa Cruz is full of charms that include and transcend its tourist-spot reputation! Don't miss going to the beach - the boardwalk for tourist tradition, or colorful Capitola, or one of many secluded coves such as Bonny Doon Beach. Enjoy the chic Pacif
notes: We do charge 20 extra per person over 2 people, including babies and children. Please check with us if you plan on bringing a young child, as the wall between the two rooms is thin and we want all our guests to have a good experience!
transit: The bus line runs on Empire Grade just a quarter mile away down a private road, and you are welcome to investigate it. Having private transport is highly recommended, though. Parking is simple and abundant. The nearest airport is Monterey, which is quite nice, though it's small - SFO is just over an hour away. Rental cars are abundantly available there. Taxis and Uber are difficult to find in this area.
host_about:
Hi there! I'm a friendly and thoughtful person who loves being outdoors and enjoys making things. The varieties of human experience are fascinating to me - I'm an anthropology graduate student and avid reader. I delight in gardening, good food, and spending time with my sweet huge horse. 

As a host, my partner Karim and I are cheerful and warm, happy either to get to know you or to give you space, whichever you're in the mood for. Enjoy privacy on the deck for your morning tea, sit with us by the fire and share a glass of wine and travel stories, gather up tips for all the good spots to eat and play nearby. We have lived all over the Bay Area and know it well - I am a native Californian and Karim is a charming French transplant. We share our home with a delightful dog who is extremely mellow and friendly with people - he's a medium size English Setter / Australian Shepherd mix - and a grey cat who loves to be pet. Between us, we have traveled to over 30 countries and have lived in Germany, Ghana, Italy, and Sweden.

space: The Dake House as it is known in the Santa Cruz Historic Registry, was built in 1904 by Clarence Dake with the generous support of his wife’s family money. He was a gentleman farmer and started the first escrow/title business in Santa Cruz. The house sits on a hill overlooking the town of Santa Cruz, the mission and the sweeping views of the Monterey Bay and the Boardwalk. While High Street is centrally located of the main routes to UCSC, most of the 2/3 acre property is surrounded by nature. Red tail hawks soar and perch in the tall trees, deer regularly come by to graze, and the hummingbirds love all the salvias in the garden.  The ‘Heavenly View Room with Queen Poster Bed” is spacious room with a firm,  comfortable queen bed with wood poster bed frame.  Located on the second floor, on southeast side of the house, the room has 10’ coved ceilings, antique lighting, antique desk and dresser, a mini refrigerator in the closet. name: Classic Beach Bungalow - Seabright
summary: This classic craftsman bungalow sits just two blocks from the entrance to Seabright Beach.  This Beach House has three bedrooms and two baths (tubs/showers in each). The bedrooms provide tranquil retreat after enjoying the beach.The large porch is great for lounging while watching beach goers come and go.
space: The Seabright neighborhood (called Midtown by local surfers) is centrally located and minutes to numerous desirable attractions such as the beach, Boardwalk Amusement Park, Yacht Harbor, West Cliff Drive, UCSC and so on. This Beach Bungalow is also a great base for regional day trips to Monterey, Carmel, Big Sur, Silicon Valley, Half Moon Bay and San Francisco.  Closer to home, actually just a few blocks away,  in case you don't feel like driving, there are several restaurants (Seabright Brewery, La Posta, Triamonti's Pizza and Pasta, Linda's Sea Breeze Cafe and Betty Burgers) and a couple cafes (Java Junction with Free WiFi and Verve Cafe with excellent espresso). In the nearby Yacht Harbor there is Aldo's Cafe and the Crow's Nest Bar and Grill; both have great ocean views. Regardless of whether you plan to stay put or see the many sites in the area, the Mott Beach Bungalow is a wonderful home base and place to stay.

neighborhood_overview: This classic craftsman bungalow sits just two blocks from the entrance to Seabright Beach, the best beach in Santa Cruz. In a neighborhood laid out in the 1880s, this early 1900s home marks the transition from beach shack to beach house.  You can leave your car in the driveway and walk to the beach, Boardwalk, Yacht Harbor or any the neighborhood shops including Betty's Burgers (grass fed), Linda Seabreeze Cafe (great breakfast), Seabright Brewery (pints of local brew),  Brady's Yacht Club (great dive bar), Java Junction (free WiFi), Verve Cafe (beans roasted onsite), La Posta Restaurant, Tramonti (Italian style pizza) and others.
transit: The Seabright Beach Neighborhood is very walkable.  You can also bike along to coast - West Cliff Drive is a great ride with the Lighthouse House midway to Natural Bridges State Park. Outside of the neighborhood and scenic bike rides you need a car to get around the town and the region.

neighborhood_overview: We are very close to a cute little park called Jose Park. We are about 3 miles from the Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk. A bit of long walk, but certainly a super close drive. We are very close to Sunny Cove Beach. When my husband and I walk it takes about 20 minutes. If you come during off season you can usually find parking by the beach, but during summer it can be extremely difficult. The beaches are beautiful and worth the walk though :)
transit: We are right next to a bus stop. It's a quick ride to downtown or to Capitola. The bus is 2 per adult and it comes about every 30 minutes. As far as driving goes we are located in "mid town". As the name implies we are in the middle of Santa Cruz. Not too far from the west or east side of things. We have quick access to the freeway.
host_about:
My husband Jason and I are Santa Cruz residents that enjoy being active in the beautiful outdoor spaces Santa Cruz has to offer. We have two dogs that love to tag along with us on our adventures. Their favorite place to go is the beach. I am going to have to agree with them there :)

It's the simple things in life and the experiences we have that define us. We hope that Santa Cruz can be apart of your travel journey.

neighborhood_overview: I love everything about this neighborhood.  I love how I know my neighbors.  I love how walking down to check the surf is difficult just because of the friends you see along the way.  We don't have sidewalks and we like it that way. What we have are backyard bbqs and each other.
notes: There are always hidden gems from talking with locals. -Restaurants, beaches, nature walks, yoga studios, health food stores etc…If you are happy doing your own thing that is perfect.  If you would like the inside scoop I would be happy to share. ;-)
transit: Santa Cruz is small and Pleasure Point even smaller.  You can use your car or take the bus from the bus stop just down the street.  But if you just want to use the bikes provided or stay on foot you will be just fine.
host_about: Hey Airbnb folks thanks for taking the time to check out my profile and the Pleasure Point beach cottage.  I've now spent most of my life in Santa Cruz and I am a big fan of keeping the integrity of Pleasure Point, architecturally and as a community. My house was built in 1928 which is a big representation of the history of this area.  As this area was once one of the last "surf ghettos" in California it is known by its sweet beach cottages and community feel.  I pride myself on maintaining my cottage for others so they can experience old Santa Cruz.  Traveling and surfing or maybe surfing and traveling are a few of the greatest loves in my life. There is so much to be learned when visiting other places, peoples and stepping outside our comfort zone.  My love for surfing has taken me across the globe and I've definitely seen there is always an exchange in life:  In order to get respect it is important to give respect.  I've been humbled more than once in the ocean and on land. ;-)  Please enjoy enjoy enjoy Santa Cruz and this sweet little cottage in the heart of Pleasure Point.  Bienvenidos.

neighborhood_overview: Pleasure Point is a safe, friendly neighborhood. We are 1 1/2 blocks to World class Surfing Reserve  with 8+ surf breaks.  People walk or bike with their dogs, and family along cliff or on the beach.    The Point Cafe and store (1 block) serves great food & has outdoor seating. My son, Peter, lives in the house; he is a chef at a well know Hotel/Restaurant in Santa Cruz..

The house sits on a hill overlooking the town of Santa Cruz, the mission and the sweeping views of the Monterey Bay and the Boardwalk. While High Street is centrally located of the main routes to UCSC, most of the 2/3 acre property is surrounded by nature. Red tail hawks soar and perch in the tall trees, deer regularly come by to graze, and the hummingbirds love all the salvias in the garden.  The  "Peach Room" is cozy and peaceful room with a firm, comfortable queen bed on an iron frame.  Located on the sec
neighborhood_overview: This is a central location, easily accessible from Mission Street/Highway 1, on the #10 bus line (to and from the nearby UCSC), a few minutes drive (or 10 minute walk) to downtown, hiking trails of the Pogonip, the arboretum, and near all the attractions of the Santa Cruz beach, West Cliff and boardwalk.
transit: Airport-We are about 40 minutes to San Jose International Airport (SJC). San Francisco Airport (SFO) is about 1 hour and 30 minutes without traffic. Los Angeles Airport (LAX) is about a 6 hour drive to the south using the fastest routes.  Train-Amtrak train is about 30 minutes away (in Salinas). You can take a connector bus from downtown Santa Cruz metro station.  Walking to Downtown: Go downhill (East) on High Street. Cross over Highway 1 bridge. Continue on High Street. Cross park diagonally. Cross at crosswalk and walk down hill on Water Street. The Clock Tower and Pacific Avenue are at the bottom of the hill. Downtown will be to your right.  Other walking destinations: it is about a 20 minute uphill walk through a residential neighborhood to get to the hiking trails of the Pogonip. I recommend going down High Street to Highland. Make a left and walk up Highland to Spring Street. Pogonip trails are at the end of Spring Street.  Bus #10 High Street bus will take you to UCSC. (nearest

neighborhood_overview: The villa is located one block from the ocean and scenic West Cliff Drive. There are are several great beaches, quiet hidden coves and scenic bay views within minutes of your front door. Hop on one of our bikes to explore the neighborhood. You can shop for fresh produce at the farmer’s market, sample a pint at a local brewery, get buzzed on caffeine or taste a flight of fantastic wine.  With 29 beaches surrounding the city, Santa Cruz is famous for world-class waves and cliff walks. Go beyond the beach to find miles of forested mountain bike trails, a top research University, you-pick organic farms and coffee shops brimming with hipsters, hippies and entrepreneurs.
transit: Santa Cruz is easy to get around by bike or car. There is free parking in front of the Villa and you can rent a house bike and get downtown in 10 minutes.  - 1h20 min from San Francisco International Airport  - 40 min from San Jose Airport.  - Airport picks up and drop off can be organized. - Try using Skyscanner when you select your travel dates.  (If you live in the Bay area and don’t have a car, you can either take the Greyhound bus or the Cal train to San Jose, then catch the highway 17 bus to downtown Santa Cruz). THE SCENIC ROUTE TO & FROM SF: Take the slightly slower scenic route along the "Slow Coast" from Pacifica past Half Moon Bay, through Pescadero and Davenport. Be sure to check out the surf along the way and grab a few tacos at the Gas Station in Pescadero (Mercado & Taqueria De Amigos).

When we are home we travel almost exclusively by bike. Our location is very convenient for public transportation.  The bus stop is around the corner that takes you directly to downtown Santa Cruz. The local bus service hooks up with service to San Jose, Caltrain, and all the Bay Area Transit systems including both San Jose and San Francisco Airports. From the airport, use Bay Area Transit system to Diridon Station in San Jose. From there you can catch the Hwy 17 Express to Santa Cruz. From the Santa Cruz downtown station take Santa Cruz Metro Bus 66 or 68 (Live Oak) to the bus stop nearest the intersection of 17th and Portola. The intersection is 2 blocks from our house. The Cowboy Room has a queen size log bed, and a twin. It has a private deck overlooking the redwoods and a wood fired stove. Sleeps 3 comfortably. Extra charge of 50 for third person in room. notes: Breakfast is served 8am to 10:30am. Please let us know if you have special dietary needs!  Late check out may be possible by advance arrangement without charge.
transit: The Wilder Ranch mountain bike, hiking and equestrian trails are one mile away. The Santa Cruz bus stop is 1/4 mile away, 25 minute trip to town. Surfing is two miles away. Charming Davenport is 3 miles away. Public buses stop 1/8 mile from the ranch, but may not have practical schedules.
host_about:
My love of food, cooking, wine and art has lead me on a lifelong journey. Years ago, I was a restauranteur in Chicago, then a full time studio potter, then a career in corporate sales and marketing.

I've traveled extensively, usually on a quest to find indigenous, traditional regional foods. Desert beans in India, grilled squid from a street vendor in Hong Kong, fresh rambutan in Thailand, black mole in Mexico, and hay soup in Austria are just a few memorable tastes. I am inspired by these experiences and I cook with international flavors.

A few years ago, I began to dream about having a farm where I could produce more of the foods, meats, and wines that I love. That dream came true when we bought FlipJack Ranch. Ranch life suits me, waking up to gather fresh eggs, cuddling the baby chicks, wrangling the goats, walking out to see the wooly pigs with a cup of coffee in hand. The whole 'farm to table' thing is real here on the ranch and the sustainable, organic and free range food products are my inspiration for daily menus. I love to forage too, here or nearby,  bringing back mushrooms, salad greens or mussels for the table. 

As a traveler myself, I value warm hospitality and those little things that make a stay memorable. I love it when I can go to a place and just unwind, assured that everything is there and I can just relax. I hope to make your stay with us memorable.

summary: Our large sunny studio attached to a 1940's barn in the Santa Cruz mountains above Hwy 1. Opt for a quiet weekend on the property or venture out for easy access to wine tasting, biking, hiking, surfing or playing on the rugged north county beaches.
space: Each day as we drive up the mountain to our home we feel the rest of the world slipping away. If you are looking to get away to a quiet, rural location where you can easily access trails for riding or hiking, north coast beaches, wine tasting and dining  - this is your spot.   We live on a 1.5 acre property that is open and sunny, at the edge of the redwood forest.  The studio you will be staying in has it's own access, it is over 450 square feet and is attached to the barn, which is over a 150 feet  from the main house. The studio is heated and contains:  • King size bed  • Full bathroom  • Futon couch   • TV & DVD player - no cable  • WiFi  • Closets & dresser for clothes storage  • Dining table and chairs for two  • Small refrigerator  • Toaster oven  • Microwave  • Electric Kettle  • Cutlery, plates, bowls, cups and mugs  • Knives, can opener & bottle opener  • Phone (landline) cell phone service is     unreliable We do not have a kitchen in the studio but feel free to bring prepar

The studio you will be staying in has it's own access, it is over 450 square feet and is attached to the barn, which is over a 150 feet  from the main house. The studio is heated and contains:  • King size bed  • Full bathroom  • Futon couch   • TV & DVD player - no cable  • WiFi  • Closets & dresser for clothes storage  • Dining table and chairs for two  • Small refrigerator
neighborhood_overview: We live in a small rural neighborhood where all of the lots are at least 1 acre.  At night don't be surprised to hear coyotes or owls, and when it's clear with no moon the stars are bright and you can see the Milky Way.  The neighborhood is quiet, and we ask our guests to be respectful of the quiet and the overall environment.   Our larger neighborhood includes Davenport and many beautiful and rugged beaches along Highway 1.  If you would like to hear about local hikes and beaches please ask us. Easy access to State Parks:  • Fall Creek ~5 minutes • Coast Dairies ~10 minutes • Wilder Ranch ~15 minutes • Big Basin (Waddell Beach) ~20 minutes • Ano Nuevo - under 25 minutes
notes: We are a multi-generational family of 5 living on the property.  We have two young kids who always love to meet new people but we also respect the privacy of our guests.  During your stay we will be around - gardening, playing, etc., feel free to come out and say hello. The barn contains a small woodshop that is sometimes used for periods of time during the day.  We will do our best to not be involved in any projects while you're here, but on occasion you may hear the sound of a wood saw or hammering. The county of Santa Cruz requires that all Airbnb hosts collect an 11% Transient Occupancy Tax (same as hotels). As Airbnb at this time does not have a way in which to collect this tax as part of your fees, we ask our guests upon departure, to please leave 11% of their room charge, either by cash or check, in order to pay this tax to the county of Santa Cruz.  Thank you!
transit: Expect winding mountain roads on your way to and from our house.  Take your time and enjoy the views along the way up & down the mountain.  Easiest driving access is from Highway 1 .  The alternate access is from Highway 17 to Felton  Empire Road, if you're looking for extended twisting mountains roads this is the road for you!  Bus stop a 3 minute walk from the house - the bus will take you to Santa Cruz...slowly. Parking is  close to the studio, free, safe & easy. Davenport is 10 minutes from the house. Santa Cruz westside is 20 minutes from the house.
host_about:
We are a multi-generational family that loves cooking, gardening, hiking, biking and playing at the beach.  Favorite travel destinations include: Big Sur, Pt. Reyes National Seashore, Yosemite, Vietnam, Thailand, Italy.  A couple of favored authors: Steinbeck, Tom Robbins  A few favorite musicians: Tom Waits, Bjork, Grateful Dead

We are a social family but are also respectful of quiet and privacy. We think we live in a beautiful area and would be happy to share it with others.

My work schedule is a little unpredicatable these days but I work 2 ten hour days dur

notes: I try to provide breakfast for guests as well.  If you have a specific breakfast request please let me know ahead for time so I can plan to have it for you if possible.  If I am home in the morning to make something up (pancakes, eggs, waffles) then great otherwise you can help yourself to what ever you need.
transit: Bus stop right around the corner.  Walking/biking distance to many places
host_about:
Well, I am in my 30's and married to my wonderful husband, Daniel for the past 6 years.  Our children include our amazing dog and our beautiful horse that mean the world to us.  By day, I work in the veterinary field and my husband teaches environmental science to kids.  During our free time, together we enjoy traveling, snow boarding, rock climbing, scuba diving, music festivals and camping.  My biggest passion is horseback riding and my husband is a die hard surfer who also enjoys working in the garden and relaxing in his hammock while listening to reggae tunes.  We are both very passionate about the environment and doing our part to reduce our footprint on this planet. 
 We love traveling and seeing the world and we make an effort to travel out of the county about every other year.  We have been to places such as Indonesia, Thailand, Malaysia, Costa Rica, Panama, Nicaragua, Hawaii, Europe, Philippines and Sri Lanka.   When we travel, we travel without any specific agenda and let life guide us to where we belong.  All we need is our trusty Lonely Planet guide book and we find ourselves at great hostels where like minded travelers gather to share stories and experiences.  We enjoy good company and fun positive people that inspire us to become better individuals.  We are fortunate in where we live and the beautiful home we live in and we would be blessed to share it with others while we are out on our own life adventures.  Our motto in life: "Find what you love and love what you find."

summary: A 3-bedroom home with a huge backyard, a garage full of surfboards and toys for the kids, only 2 blocks from the beach!
space: Hello and thank you for looking! Our 3-bedroom home is located only two blocks from the beach and world-class surf. We live in a wonderful beach community called Pleasure Point on the East Side of Santa Cruz. The house is located at the end of a dead-end street, so it's very quiet. You can hear the waves crashing! The house is a 2-story duplex. Downstairs is the open kitchen with bar, dining room and living room with hardwood floors. Vibrant colors, open floor plan and a fully stocked kitchen. Upstairs we have the master bedroom with a king bed, an office with a crib and the kids' room with a toddler bed, changing table, tons of boy and girl toys etc.

This may be fun if you are traveling with older kids who like to "camp". There is a garage full of toys (surfboards, bikes, skateboar
neighborhood_overview: Pleasure Point is a very cool surfer community that consists of a mix of older homes and "true" locals, vacation homes and larger, newer homes. Over the last 5+ years, a bunch of new shops and restaurants have opened in the neighborhood and now we are in walking distance to at least 5 restaurants, an amazing coffee shop and some retail options. There are also 2 gyms (one CrossFit) within walking distance.
notes: We do have two very sweet cats (Jack and Lexie) that are very mellow and used to little kids.
transit: There is a bus stop about 3 blocks from our house but I have never used the bus. I heard you can take it to the West Side and the Mall? :)
host_about:
I'm new to Airbnb but we've done numerous exchanges through another site where we swapped houses and had a great experience. 

Now that we have two kids, we like to travel a little bit less "rustic"...a tent and a economy rental car are things of the past. So, in order to afford a vacation rental etc., it helps out a lot to be able to rent out home. 

You will find our house very comfortable and clean, the neighborhood and neighbors absolutely charming and everything else about Pleasure Point just delightful. We absolutely love living here - but need to travel sometimes to come home and appreciate it even more!

neighborhood_overview: We live on a street that only serves the local High School, which means that it is very quiet here when school is not in session. You can hear the sea lions, and on very quiet nights you can hear the waves!  In the morning you see the sunrise from the bed. The walkability of our spot makes it essential Santa Cruz. We are one mile from the beach and boardwalk and a quarter mile from downtown. The beach is a short 5 minute bike ride or 20 minute walk.  Even closer to home, walk a few blocks to Emily’s Bakery, Sabieng Thai, or Taqueria Vallarta. We are also only a few blocks from an organic grocery and health store.   Our neighborhood is filled with some of the oldest Victorian’s in the City; including ours. This property was established in 1888. However, the cottage was built in 2006.
notes: We have a large, friendly husky "Nershi" in the backyard. He loves new people and full moons. Unfortunately, we cannot take other dogs because of him.
transit: You do not need a car to experience Santa Cruz from our house. Everything you want to see in Santa Cruz is a walk or bike ride away - including downtown, the beach, West Cliff, tacos, an organic grocery store and a plethora of coffee shops.  The City bus station is a short ten minute walk.
host_about: We are a three person hippie, music loving family - Erin, Justin and baby Satyana. We also have a husky/wolf dog, Nershi who likes to howl. We love where we live - beaches, Redwoods, great people, amazing food, sunshine and the west coast vibe.

host_about:
We're Paul and Toki!  Here are our individual profiles:

Hello, Paul here. Santa Cruz provides many of the things I enjoy: Good, natural food, alternative life styles, beaches, woods, hiking, camping, art, wine....The list goes on. The downtown movie theater even has recliners! I'm a sucker for big-budget blockbusters.

I've traveled to many places around the world, including Germany, France, Japan, several states, including Hawaii (possibly my favorite), and of course, all over California.  I'd like to visit England, The Netherlands, and Australia someday.  When I travel, I like to be out for at least a week, two if I can. I don't want to stay in one place for more than three days, as I figure I'm in a new place I may never see again; I want to see as much of it as I can. I'll see all the tourist sites, of course, but I also like to wander off and get a little lost.  Maybe go where I'm not supposed to go.

I'm obsessed with learning about health.  I'm not someone who forces you to listen about the maladies that refined sugar can bring or anything, I keep it to myself.  I find the relationship between what we eat and think turning into the body we live in to be fascinating, and there's always more to discover and experience.

I write music occasionally, and would like to be a teacher of sorts.  I'd like to make this world of nutrition and health as exciting for others as it is for me, and I think the way its taught now (lectures, seminars, books) can be a turn off for many, even though the information can be life-saving.  I'm currently trying to figure out a way to present this fascinating material in a more engaging, entertaining way.

***********************************************

Hello, Toki Here!
  I'm from the East Coast, but my heart has always called this place Home!
Santa Cruz is my kind of town; city amenities, but a small-town, meet your friends everywhere feel that fosters kinship, kindness, and caring for our little piece of Earth. I love the mix of Art, Culture, Oddities, and Social Involvement. It's so easy, here, to get out and be active. There is always something going on, from the documented festivals and music, to the impromptu, but always reliable, marathon drum circle on the levees. People watching is one of our favorite wind-downs, and we are just minutes from Downtown by foot!
   I'm an artist and Professional Organiser. The former is my passion, as I love to create and express, verbally, musically, and through miniature art pieces and photography. I also love to cook, and am always challenged by new dietary restrictions we try out as we search for our optimal health. I love sun, and try to get as much of it as possible. It's not hard, here! My goal is to use my specific skills to help those that I reach in my interactions, be it business, personal, or otherwise. If I were to sum up my purpose here, it would be; "Leave it better than I found it"
  I love to travel, and when I do, I love to stay in small, intimate, homey places, that seem welcoming and have a bit of history. I love to feel like a part of where I'm at, so the more my accommodations welcome me, the better. I definitely love that I can provide that experience here, and have a welcoming home with healthy food, good literature,  and fresh linens ready for our out-of-town guests!

The master bedroom has a king-sized bed, gas fireplace, ceiling fan, and attached bath with oversize shower and double sinks. The two other bedrooms--one with a queen bed, the other with a double--share a newly-remodeled bath with glass shower.   (All are located upstairs). Guests will have access to the living room, with a cathedral ceiling and a wood-burning stove, the formal dining room (seats 6), and k
neighborhood_overview: Our home is located 3 miles north of downtown Santa Cruz.  We are on a private road in a rural neighborhood so there's lots of open space (but with the convenience of a little store at the end of the road). Drive to the beach (about 5 miles) or, better yet, park the car at Felton's Roaring Camp and take the open-air train through the redwoods to the beach and boardwalk.  Check out the Santa Cruz Surf Museum, or join the locals walking/running/skating on West Cliff Drive.  Hike or bike the miles of trails in Henry Cowell State Park (the back entrance is right across the road) or take a private, guided horse-back ride through the forest.  Ride a zipline through the canopy at Mount Hermon, or trek the Skyline-to-Sea Trail from Big Basin State Park to the coast.  Paddle a sea kayak through Elkhorn Slough, visit the Monterey Bay Aquarium, or enjoy shopping and dining in charming Carmel village.  Taste award-winning wines at one of the dozens of Santa Cruz mountain wineries or, if it's golf
notes: This is an excellent spot for mountain biking and hiking.  Henry Cowell State Park, which is right across the road, has 15 miles of hiking and riding trails through a variety of forested areas, including huge redwoods.  The garage is available upon request to store bicycles, surfboards, and other outdoor equipment.  Wine-tasting is also a popular past-time, since there are literally dozens of wineries nearby (which are known for their pinots).
transit: There is a local bus on the closest major road, but most guests will arrive by car. There is ample free parking in the driveway or in front of the house (which is very safe since our road is private). Guests flying into San Jose should take Highway 17 towards Santa Cruz; those flying into San Francisco can take either Highway 17 or Highway 1 toward Santa Cruz. Detailed directions will be provided upon request.
host_about: I am a middle-age woman, retired after 30 years at the University of California, Santa Cruz, and proud mom of a pretty terrific 23-year-old son.  I have been around the world twice (I'm definitely not a 5-star hotel kind of gal) and have lived in several foreign countries.   My passion is gardening, and I also love hiking through the redwoods in the park across from my house.  I eat healthy (more or less), stay relatively physically fit, and try to maintain a good mental attitude.  I suppose I am a typical Santa Cruzer, pretty laid-back about most things.  Not the best cook in the world, although I occasionally get inspired to try something creative in the kitchen.  My style of guesting/hosting?  Sharing some wine and cheese with my guest/host while getting acquainted.

You can shop for fresh produce at the farmer’s market, sample a pint at a local brewery, get buzzed on caffeine or taste a flight of fantastic wine. The few lights we see at night are from neighbor homes across the river.     Coming home from town we watch for each new crop blooming in the organic farm between the road  and the river. notes: Breakfast--   Tea, coffee, latte-        Full kitchen available to share.          Separate refrigerator for guests.
transit: Public Transit is sketchy - depending on where you go. The closest public bus stop is a mile away -- but the transit center, from which all buses leave, is less than two miles away. neighborhood_overview: Access to every type of beach living activity, amenity, and the sea! It is entirely possibly to park your car and not move it for days. Take long walks on the beach, listen to the seals playing in the harbor, build sand castles with the kids, cruise East Cliff drive on a comfy bike, Stand Up Paddle, Sea Kayak, take a jog down the coast or a romantic sunset sail on the Chardonnay II. Its an amazing slice of heaven.  The house is a 3 minute walk to the beach. A 2 minute walk to the Yacht Harbor (or less!) and a 3 minute walk to the Crow's Nest (restaurant, bar, great outdoor dining), Palomar (mexican bar & restaurant), Kind Grind (coffee), and Johnnys (great seafood restaurant). Aldo's restaurant is a fun, free boat ride across to the other side of the harbor. Probably takes 5 mins. We are about a 15-20 min stroll to the Beach Boardwalk over some lovely sea walls and bridges. It takes about 10 mins (1 mile) to get to the Seabright Brewery and restaurants on Seabright Ave. There is a pizz
notes: There is a 3-4 night minimum during the summer weeks. June - August.
transit: Walking, biking, driving are all very easy! Public transit - there is a bus that stops a block from the house on Lake Ave - check (website hidden).
host_about:
I purchased Casa de Alta Loma in 2013 as the fulfillment of a life-long dream to live close to a beautiful beach, in an environment that soothes the soul. I have lived in and around Santa Cruz for a decade now and finally decided on just the right spot (Live Oaks) and the perfect home (Alta Loma). I use it often and enjoy the environment tremendously.  For example, Stand Up Paddle in the harbor and out to sea is one of my favorite things to do - The SUP shack is minutes from my doorstep and if you're lucky, you'll see all sorts of marine life (whales too!). It's such a unique place - we even have a Saturday morning Ukelele sing-along down on the beach.  We usually get coffee at the Kind Grind (right there on the beach) and just listen.  My 4 yr. old niece has even played along with the crowd.  (Don't expect skilled musicians but do expect friendliness and old time sing-along songs.) We have a Live Oak Farmer's Market on Sunday which is fantastic too!

I love to entertain my friends and family from the East Coast at the beach house - they just cannot get over how idyllic life in Santa Cruz can be. I was born and raised outside of Boston, MA and relocated to the West Coast to work in the Software Industry. I hope you come enjoy Casa de Alta Loma and all it has to offer.
The location is ideal. You can hear the ocean, the sea lions, and the gulls but not the young neighboring renters who are right down on the beach.  It's a 2 minute walk to the harbor where you will find a favorite restaurant -- Johnny's Harborside.  It's a 4 minute walk to the beach which is wide and long. I often run the entire stretch from my beach down to the Santa Cruz Boardwalk all on the sand (at low tide!). It's about 13 minutes walk to the east entrance of the famous Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk.
Driving gets you to a lot of popular destinations: E.g., Shadowbrook restaurant in Capitola is 3 miles away and SF and Big Sur are each about an hour and a half away, in opposite directions.

neighborhood_overview: The house is located on a quiet street with two hour parking on the street and two parking spaces in front of the garage (one available for your use). Right around the corner is Westlake Park. A park with a little lake and a great playground. Kids can get their first fishing experience at the lake.  A short walk up the road will bring you to the entrance of the Pogonip, a natural preserve, with endless trails and beautiful views. We are less than ten minutes from all of the excitement at the Boardwalk (we like to ride our bikes, just coming back up the hill is a work out — takes about 15 minutes- this way we don’t have to pay for parking!). Downtown is brisk walk or a short 5 min. drive.  If you walk along West Cliff to the lighthouse you can watch the pro-surfers do their tricks at Steamers Lane. If you walk the other way on West Cliff you can visit the Monarch butterfly sanctuary at Natural Bridges State Park. We are a short ways away from the natural grocery store (New Leaf), Safewa
notes: I do not live on the premises, however I do live near by. Due to travel and family obligations, I might not always be available for check in or check out. However, please feel always free to call, email, or txt me any time you have a question or a concern.
transit: The public bus system is at the end of the street. It will take you across town. There is a ZipCar location nearby, if you are car less. Otherwise, Santa Cruz is a very bike friendly city and you can nearly bike anywhere (just bring a lock).

summary: Located halfway between Santa Cruz and the charming mountain towns of the San Lorenzo Valley, the house offers guests an en suite master bedroom, a gourmet kitchen, a comfortable living room, a beautiful yard and ample free parking on a private road.
space: Our home is suitable for adults who want a clean, quiet, beautiful space to return to after a day at the beach (just minutes away by car ) or hiking/biking in the redwoods (across the street).  Enjoy a glass of wine while watching the sunset from the beautiful yard, replete with mature trees, roses and lots of crazy hummingbirds.
description: Located halfway between Santa Cruz and the charming mountain towns of the San Lorenzo Valley, the house offers guests an en suite master bedroom, a gourmet kitchen, a comfortable living room, a beautiful yard and ample free parking on a private road. The en suite master bedroom, with gas fireplace and ceiling fan, comfortably sleeps two.  (It is located upstairs).  Guests will have access to the living room and kitchen as well.  Guests have acccess to wi-fi. The owners will be present to greet guests unless other arrangements are made in advance.  Interaction with guests is at the discretion of the guests. Our home is located on a private road in a semi-rural
neighborhood_overview: Our home is located on a private road in a semi-rural neighborhood so there's lots of open space (but with the convenience of a little store at the end of the road).  We are right across the road from the Henry Cowell State Park and a quarter mile to the renowned Pasatiempo Golf Course.  The Santa Cruz main beach is less than 10 minutes away by car, as is San Lorenzo Valley, home to Felton's Roaring Camp Railroad  and Hallcrest Vineyards (killer Pinot!), as well as Mount Hermon's Redwood Canopy Tours (zip-lining).  Further up the valley is the Big Basin  Redwoods State Park, with it's Skyline-to-the-Sea Trail, the Boulder Creek golf course and several organic farms which offer tours and farm-to-table dinners. Santa Cruz offers walking and biking on West Cliff Drive (where you can watch the surfers ride the waves) , beautiful beaches, the famous boardwalk, incredible restaurants, music venues, museums, and the Pacific Garden Mall.
notes: This is an excellent spot for mountain biking and hiking.  Henry Cowell State Park, which is right across the road, has 15 miles of hiking and riding trails through a variety of forested areas, including huge redwoods.  The garage is available upon request to store bicycles, surfboards, and other outdoor equipment.  Wine-tasting is also a popular past-time, since there are literally dozens of wineries nearby.
transit: There is a local bus on the closest major road, but most guests will arrive by car.  There is ample free parking in the driveway or in front of the house (which is very safe since our road is private).  Guests flying into San Jose should take Highway 17 towards Santa Cruz; those flying into San Francisco can take either Highway 17 or Highway 1 toward Santa Cruz.  Detailed directions will be provided upon request.
host_about: I am a middle-age woman, retired after 30 years at the University of California, Santa Cruz, and proud mom of a pretty terrific 23-year-old son.  I have been around the world twice (I'm definitely not a 5-star hotel kind of gal) and have lived in several foreign countries.   My passion is gardening, and I also love hiking through the redwoods in the park across from my house.  I eat healthy (more or less), stay relatively physically fit, and try to maintain a good mental attitude.  I suppose I am a typical Santa Cruzer, pretty laid-back about most things.  Not the best cook in the world, although I occasionally get inspired to try something creative in the kitchen.  My style of guesting/hosting?  Sharing some wine and cheese with my guest/host while getting acquainted.

neighborhood_overview: This apartment is located in the Pleasure Point neighborhood of Santa Cruz.  This cliff-side neighborhood hosts spectacular views of the Monterey Bay, beaches with tide pools and infamous surf spots. Inland from the cliffs are restaurants including the Chill Out Cafe, Verve Coffee Roasters, the Penny Ice Creamery and Pleasure Point Pizza (2 slice on Tuesdays!).  If you are seeking some adventure, Pleasure Point hosts wetsuit, surfboard, kayak, scuba driving and sailing rentals and tours. We are also just minutes from downtown Santa Cruz, the Boardwalk as well as downtown Capitola shopping.  For beautiful cliff-side scenery and surf-watching, walk or jog the walkway on E. Cliff Drive between 41st Ave and 32nd Ave.  Live Oak Beach is an enjoyable 8 minute walk from the apartment complex.  This beach and adjacent neighborhood streets require a residential parking permit on summer weekends.  However, just down the road is Moran Lake Beach, which has a small parking lot (with restrooms) th
notes: We also only offer on-street parking, which is free and has no time limitations.  The apartment is part of a large apartment complex.  Generally, my neighbors are quiet and friendly.  I have only had one complaint from guests about noise from neighbors, which was on a major holiday weekend (you must be forgiving of holiday celebration noise).  This apartment is often described by guests as being quiet, especially in relation to downtown or motels located near the freeway.
transit: Having a car or bike is recommended for this apartment location.  However, there is a bus stop one block away on Portola Rd. that runs hourly buses to downtown Santa Cruz. The closest beach is an enjoyable 8 minute stroll from the apartment.
host_about: Hi, I'm a busy professional, but I also love to travel.  I hope you can appreciate my cozy apartment as a respite on your journeys.  I do my best to make it as clean and comfortable as possible and am excited to share my knowledge of the Santa Cruz area with you.

space: Our little studio is the perfect charming hideaway for a couple or small family visiting Santa Cruz. A short 10 minute stroll to the beach and boardwalk, or a 5 minute walk to downtown makes this the ideal spot to enjoy Santa Cruz without a car.  The studio shares a wall with the owner's house, and shares the yard with us, 6 chickens, a cat, and a dog on the weekdays.  There is a family next door with 2 young children who often come over to play, and we own the backyard next door, which means you have a beautiful large garden to play in!  The garden includes an outdoor kingsize bed, many fruit trees, a teepee covered in beans, and a mulberry bush fort for children to hide in and pick mulberries.  A private porch is perfect for lounging around in the afternoons.  Breakfast can be arranged for an additional fee.  The owners own Santa Cruz Pedicab, so private pedicab rides to the beach, Boardwalk, or downtown can be arranged for an additional fee.
